<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="151" type="distribution">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="151">Distribution.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="151">
This species has been previously recorded from Algeria, Egypt, Sudan, Israel, Jordan, Saudi Arabia and, provisionally, Iran. Thus, the current record from UAE is the easternmost in the whole known range of the species (
<bibRefCitation author="Zamani, A" journalOrPublisher="ZooKeys" pageId="0" pageNumber="151" pagination="17 - 41" title="The spider genus Pterotricha in Iran, with the description of a new genus (Araneae, Gnaphosidae)." url="https://doi.org/10.3897/zookeys.777.26745" volume="777" year="2018">Zamani et al. 2018</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="151" type="comments">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="151">Comments.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="151">
The identification of the females are to be considered as provisional: their epigynes are similar to that of 
<taxonomicName class="Arachnida" family="Gnaphosidae" genus="Pterotricha" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Pterotricha dalmasi" order="Araneae" pageId="0" pageNumber="151" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="dalmasi">Pterotricha cf. dalmasi</taxonomicName>
reported from southern Iran by 
<bibRefCitation author="Zamani, A" journalOrPublisher="ZooKeys" pageId="0" pageNumber="151" pagination="17 - 41" title="The spider genus Pterotricha in Iran, with the description of a new genus (Araneae, Gnaphosidae)." url="https://doi.org/10.3897/zookeys.777.26745" volume="777" year="2018">Zamani et al. (2018)</bibRefCitation>
and that illustrated by 
<bibRefCitation author="Levy, G" journalOrPublisher="Journal of Natural History" pageId="0" pageNumber="151" pagination="919 - 981" title="Revision of the spider subfamily Gnaphosinae in Israel (Araneae: Gnaphosidae)." url="https://doi.org/10.1080/00222939500770351" volume="29" year="1995">Levy (1995</bibRefCitation>
: fig. 75) from Israel; it is possible that they belong to the currently undescribed female of 
<taxonomicName class="Arachnida" family="Gnaphosidae" genus="Pterotricha" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Pterotricha kovblyuki" order="Araneae" pageId="0" pageNumber="151" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="kovblyuki">Pterotricha kovblyuki</taxonomicName>
Zamani &amp; Marusik, 2018, and the species could potentially have a larger range than what is currently known for it.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
